1
00:00:04,953 --> 00:00:06,155
Hi, I'm Brandon Sheffield.

2
00:00:06,837 --> 00:00:08,340
I am the director of Microsoft Games

3
00:00:08,380 --> 00:00:10,043
and I'm here to talk to you about taste

4
00:00:10,605 --> 00:00:11,967
and how to cultivate it in your games

5
00:00:12,007 --> 00:00:13,170
and how you all have it probably.

6
00:00:13,990 --> 00:00:16,011
There are too many games like these.

7
00:00:16,071 --> 00:00:19,612
They all look basically the same and give no sense of character or taste whatsoever.

8
00:00:19,932 --> 00:00:23,193
You look at a screenshot and you think, yeah, I've seen that, I know what that is.

9
00:00:24,194 --> 00:00:29,916
These games, on the other hand, regardless of whether you like them, come from a foundation

10
00:00:29,956 --> 00:00:30,556
of taste.

11
00:00:31,276 --> 00:00:35,338
You can see that someone had a perspective, something to communicate, and they went with

12
00:00:35,398 --> 00:00:35,438
it.

13
00:00:36,959 --> 00:00:40,522
You look at a screen here and you might think I haven't seen that, I'm curious about it

14
00:00:40,742 --> 00:00:42,023
or that's too weird for me.

15
00:00:42,324 --> 00:00:46,127
But either way, it's got your attention and as we all know, getting attention is extremely

16
00:00:46,147 --> 00:00:46,668
hard right now.

17
00:00:47,368 --> 00:00:49,130
We should make more games like these.

18
00:00:49,470 --> 00:00:52,713
There's a greater risk but potentially greater reward as well.

19
00:00:53,234 --> 00:00:57,358
And why be an independent game developer if you don't want to take risks and do interesting

20
00:00:57,418 --> 00:00:57,698
things?

21
00:00:57,718 --> 00:00:59,300
You may as well just go join a company.

22
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:04,323
If you show your taste and your passions, people will react to it.

23
00:01:04,803 --> 00:01:08,885
People love to have opinions and they love to share their opinions against yours.

24
00:01:10,046 --> 00:01:15,349
Especially these days with YouTubers and Instagrammers and Instagram stars and all these things,

25
00:01:15,869 --> 00:01:18,631
people are increasingly defining themselves by what they like,

26
00:01:18,911 --> 00:01:20,392
whereas they used to say what they do.

27
00:01:20,512 --> 00:01:22,693
They used to say, I'm a carpenter or I'm a mechanic.

28
00:01:22,813 --> 00:01:26,816
Now people say, I'm a foodie or, you know, I'm a film buff.

29
00:01:28,075 --> 00:01:31,420
If you show your taste, they will react to it.

30
00:01:31,981 --> 00:01:33,483
In between these two examples,

31
00:01:33,523 --> 00:01:34,504
there's something more like,

32
00:01:34,605 --> 00:01:36,147
this reminds me of something I liked

33
00:01:36,247 --> 00:01:37,409
that I thought nobody else did.

34
00:01:39,131 --> 00:01:41,315
You want people to feel as though

35
00:01:41,335 --> 00:01:43,217
you made your game just for them.

36
00:01:44,514 --> 00:01:49,137
Our game that we just released, Odeer, comes from the tradition of super scalers.

37
00:01:49,237 --> 00:01:53,819
I can't necessarily say this is the best representation of completely different tastes because driving

38
00:01:53,839 --> 00:01:57,482
games exist, but we did it in a different way.

39
00:01:58,822 --> 00:02:02,084
The technology is old because it's all pseudo 3D.

40
00:02:02,104 --> 00:02:03,265
There's no actual 3D in it.

41
00:02:03,345 --> 00:02:05,947
It's all scaling sprites, and we added some weird shaders and stuff.

42
00:02:06,487 --> 00:02:07,168
So we took...

43
00:02:07,828 --> 00:02:11,610
something that was old and added some twists to it and it made people say, oh man, this

44
00:02:11,650 --> 00:02:14,192
is just what I was waiting for, or you made this just for me.

45
00:02:14,572 --> 00:02:18,395
On the other hand, we had tons of people say, what is this Atari trash?

46
00:02:20,817 --> 00:02:27,421
But either way for us, it shows that we're staying true to ourselves and we made the

47
00:02:27,441 --> 00:02:28,842
game that we wanted to make.

48
00:02:28,882 --> 00:02:33,685
It's not important that people agree with you, but that you know what you like and you

49
00:02:33,705 --> 00:02:34,065
make that.

50
00:02:36,062 --> 00:02:39,784
If you mix the unexpected with the familiar, you've got a great platform to stand on.

51
00:02:39,944 --> 00:02:46,788
Obviously, Overwatch is a great FPS that has layered on top of it someone's taste.

52
00:02:47,328 --> 00:02:52,811
If this game, just being a great FPS, if that's all it were, if it used assets from the Unity

53
00:02:52,851 --> 00:02:54,892
store that were generic, it wouldn't be nearly as popular.

54
00:02:56,293 --> 00:03:00,577
So people say that taste is something that you have or don't, and I completely disagree.

55
00:03:00,697 --> 00:03:04,962
I believe it can be cultivated and that all of you are capable of self-analysis.

56
00:03:05,382 --> 00:03:08,986
And I don't believe it's objective, it's entirely related to the individual.

57
00:03:09,366 --> 00:03:12,490
So here are a few exercises to bring your own taste out.

58
00:03:13,370 --> 00:03:13,831
Very important.

59
00:03:15,271 --> 00:03:17,532
Think about your top 10 favorite songs or albums.

60
00:03:17,652 --> 00:03:20,714
Write three sentences about them and why you like each one.

61
00:03:21,454 --> 00:03:23,515
What was going on in your life when you heard them first?

62
00:03:24,035 --> 00:03:25,155
Why did they resonate with you then?

63
00:03:25,456 --> 00:03:26,856
Do they resonate the same way now?

64
00:03:27,276 --> 00:03:29,197
Are there any tensions between when you listened to it

65
00:03:29,237 --> 00:03:30,858
back then and when you listen to it now

66
00:03:30,898 --> 00:03:32,038
and is that interesting in any way?

67
00:03:32,499 --> 00:03:33,879
Watch a movie that your friend likes

68
00:03:33,979 --> 00:03:35,380
but which you don't or the reverse.

69
00:03:36,020 --> 00:03:38,141
Talk about your feelings while being respectful

70
00:03:38,161 --> 00:03:39,081
of the other person's views.

71
00:03:40,328 --> 00:03:43,872
Don't force yourself to break down why it doesn't work for one of you but does for the

72
00:03:43,912 --> 00:03:44,112
other.

73
00:03:44,212 --> 00:03:46,554
Don't focus on why someone else is wrong.

74
00:03:46,654 --> 00:03:50,337
Focus on why you believe what you believe, why you feel what you feel.

75
00:03:51,178 --> 00:03:53,700
Go to a thrift store and find three things of interest there.

76
00:03:53,740 --> 00:03:55,061
You don't have to buy them or anything.

77
00:03:55,101 --> 00:03:58,344
Just find interesting things that appeal to you or seem weird.

78
00:03:58,925 --> 00:03:59,925
What makes them interesting?

79
00:04:00,846 --> 00:04:02,388
Who do you think owned these things?

80
00:04:02,488 --> 00:04:03,509
Why did they get rid of them?

81
00:04:03,769 --> 00:04:04,950
What were the circumstances there?

82
00:04:06,161 --> 00:04:09,723
If you're lucky enough to be able to travel, go anywhere, even if it's a few towns over.

83
00:04:10,124 --> 00:04:14,207
Avoid tourist spots and instead go to a specific restaurant, a thrift store, find something

84
00:04:14,267 --> 00:04:16,729
on Yelp, somewhere else that's very local.

85
00:04:17,129 --> 00:04:18,170
Don't take the easy road.

86
00:04:18,310 --> 00:04:18,950
Get lost.

87
00:04:19,211 --> 00:04:19,791
Walk around.

88
00:04:19,851 --> 00:04:21,613
You'll learn a lot about people and about yourself.

89
00:04:22,799 --> 00:04:24,020
So how do you apply this to games?

90
00:04:25,362 --> 00:04:26,905
Once you know who you are and what you like,

91
00:04:27,005 --> 00:04:28,047
it comes really naturally.

92
00:04:28,587 --> 00:04:30,671
Why should this character be blue when it could be red?

93
00:04:30,891 --> 00:04:32,894
Is there a reason for this person to be a man?

94
00:04:33,254 --> 00:04:34,056
What if it were a woman?

95
00:04:34,136 --> 00:04:35,738
What if it were genderless?

96
00:04:35,818 --> 00:04:36,860
What if it had a dog?

97
00:04:37,661 --> 00:04:39,982
What are people who you know who have dogs like?

98
00:04:40,142 --> 00:04:41,702
How would they react in this situation?

99
00:04:42,262 --> 00:04:44,503
Make sure you're asking and answering these questions constantly.

100
00:04:44,943 --> 00:04:46,303
Make choices that matter in your games.

101
00:04:46,723 --> 00:04:48,164
Don't do something because it's popular.

102
00:04:48,204 --> 00:04:52,825
Do it because it means something to you or to your mom or to your team or to your third

103
00:04:52,865 --> 00:04:53,365
grade teacher.

104
00:04:53,905 --> 00:04:57,346
When you make something for yourself or for someone you know, it's more likely to resonate

105
00:04:57,366 --> 00:04:59,006
with others because it will be genuine and real.

106
00:05:00,207 --> 00:05:05,471
People respect taste. They crave a connection to it and want to be complimented for having thoughts and feelings.

107
00:05:05,932 --> 00:05:09,254
Everyone has the capacity to do this. Some people have an easier time than others,

108
00:05:09,575 --> 00:05:14,839
but everyone is capable of identifying what they like and acting on it. I don't care if your taste

109
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:17,320
Taste leads to a rhythm game with only smash mouth covers.

110
00:05:17,440 --> 00:05:19,601
Just make something that means something to you.

111
00:05:20,182 --> 00:05:24,564
If you make a game infused with your carefully considered thoughts, feelings, hopes, dreams,

112
00:05:24,684 --> 00:05:28,826
and taste, your game will be so much more interesting than the next clone of something

113
00:05:28,886 --> 00:05:29,246
popular.

114
00:05:29,606 --> 00:05:32,048
There are so many bland and flavorless games in the world.

115
00:05:32,168 --> 00:05:33,588
Let's not make any more of them.

116
00:05:34,769 --> 00:05:34,889
Thanks.

117
00:05:34,909 --> 00:05:35,089
Thank you.

118
00:05:51,779 --> 00:05:52,320
One moment.

119
00:06:04,092 --> 00:06:04,913
Next up is Tanya.

120
00:06:13,853 --> 00:06:20,254
Hi everyone, I'm Tanya, the captain of Kit Fox Games, a small studio in Montreal, Canada.

121
00:06:20,474 --> 00:06:25,316
You need to know how to take care of yourself and meet your hard deadlines.

122
00:06:26,216 --> 00:06:30,897
Everyone in this room thinks probably that their number one priority is to make a great

123
00:06:30,937 --> 00:06:31,237
game.

124
00:06:31,317 --> 00:06:33,458
Yes, we all want to make a great game.

125
00:06:34,258 --> 00:06:37,199
But it's actually your number three priority, I'm afraid,

126
00:06:37,619 --> 00:06:40,420
because your number one priority, unfortunately,

127
00:06:40,921 --> 00:06:42,201
is to not die.

128
00:06:42,221 --> 00:06:46,603
And it's important that you survive

129
00:06:46,743 --> 00:06:48,764
making this hopefully great game,

130
00:06:48,964 --> 00:06:51,285
because your next game will be better.

131
00:06:52,225 --> 00:06:57,106
Okay? Get that through your head that you need to survive because you're going to keep making games,

132
00:06:57,207 --> 00:07:00,247
god damn it, and you're going to make them better and better every time.

133
00:07:01,107 --> 00:07:07,909
So who here has trouble with deadlines? Oh wow, really? And do you have trouble taking

134
00:07:07,989 --> 00:07:12,910
care of yourself while you're meeting the deadlines? All right, so I'm going to tell you a secret.

135
00:07:13,670 --> 00:07:13,991
All right?

136
00:07:14,951 --> 00:07:15,492
It's really hard.

137
00:07:17,273 --> 00:07:18,313
It is really, really hard.

138
00:07:18,333 --> 00:07:19,354
And I'm not going to lie.

139
00:07:19,374 --> 00:07:21,075
It's a constant struggle.

140
00:07:21,295 --> 00:07:23,717
And any time you succeed, you should absolutely

141
00:07:24,157 --> 00:07:27,059
take a moment and appreciate what you've done.

142
00:07:27,239 --> 00:07:29,460
Because taking care of yourself is hard.

143
00:07:30,341 --> 00:07:31,422
But you can do it.

144
00:07:31,902 --> 00:07:32,622
I believe in you.

145
00:07:33,223 --> 00:07:34,744
And you need to believe in yourself, too,

146
00:07:34,824 --> 00:07:39,327
because that is step one of my miracle cure for death.

147
00:07:40,967 --> 00:07:43,869
I know that it's possible because Kit Fox doesn't crunch.

148
00:07:44,109 --> 00:07:48,252
We do a couple of weeks of overtime here and there as needed, but we made both Shattered

149
00:07:48,272 --> 00:07:53,335
Planet and Moon Hunters without burnout and these other much superior games were also

150
00:07:53,395 --> 00:07:54,396
made without burnout.

151
00:07:54,536 --> 00:07:55,757
So it is possible.

152
00:07:56,297 --> 00:07:56,537
All right.

153
00:07:56,557 --> 00:07:57,458
So now everyone believes.

154
00:07:57,538 --> 00:07:58,038
It's possible.

155
00:07:58,198 --> 00:07:58,458
Great.

156
00:07:58,819 --> 00:07:59,279
What next?

157
00:08:00,760 --> 00:08:05,883
So the next thing is those of you who haven't set specific work hours, cut it out.

158
00:08:06,564 --> 00:08:08,504
because it's bad for you and you do less.

159
00:08:09,045 --> 00:08:10,885
You will actually accomplish more

160
00:08:11,366 --> 00:08:14,647
if you stop working so much.

161
00:08:15,567 --> 00:08:17,688
And you'll thank me, believe me.

162
00:08:19,029 --> 00:08:20,950
If you're not prioritizing your tasks.

163
00:08:21,290 --> 00:08:23,111
That's the next secret.

164
00:08:23,411 --> 00:08:25,932
We're getting into deep secret territory at this point.

165
00:08:26,893 --> 00:08:28,754
If you have a deadline coming up in a couple of weeks,

166
00:08:28,814 --> 00:08:31,276
it's really important that what you're doing right now

167
00:08:31,336 --> 00:08:34,718
is actually important, and not just urgent,

168
00:08:34,938 --> 00:08:36,819
because if you start focusing too much

169
00:08:37,159 --> 00:08:39,040
on the emails in your inbox

170
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:40,541
and the things happening tomorrow,

171
00:08:40,601 --> 00:08:43,143
you'll never actually get into the steady workflow

172
00:08:43,203 --> 00:08:44,323
that makes your game good.

173
00:08:47,030 --> 00:08:49,371
So reprioritize as often as you need.

174
00:08:49,971 --> 00:08:51,072
And estimate your tasks.

175
00:08:51,152 --> 00:08:53,072
Some of you don't estimate your tasks.

176
00:08:53,712 --> 00:08:54,392
Did you know that?

177
00:08:54,412 --> 00:08:56,333
Like, you don't actually think,

178
00:08:56,393 --> 00:08:57,733
how long is this gonna take me?

179
00:08:58,393 --> 00:08:59,734
And then when you're done with the task,

180
00:08:59,754 --> 00:09:01,334
you don't think, how long did that take me?

181
00:09:02,295 --> 00:09:02,795
Do that.

182
00:09:02,815 --> 00:09:05,735
And that is secret number four, okay?

183
00:09:05,815 --> 00:09:07,576
If you're not estimating, you should,

184
00:09:07,636 --> 00:09:09,316
because it's a skill that takes time.

185
00:09:10,537 --> 00:09:13,619
And if a deadline is coming up, and you can tell

186
00:09:13,839 --> 00:09:16,661
it's more than two weeks away, you're not gonna make it.

187
00:09:17,101 --> 00:09:20,223
So, okay, your first thought is going to be,

188
00:09:20,283 --> 00:09:21,344
let's work more.

189
00:09:21,524 --> 00:09:23,445
It's three weeks, three months away,

190
00:09:23,525 --> 00:09:26,407
but you know, if I just work harder, it'll be fine.

191
00:09:26,507 --> 00:09:28,008
No, you're gonna die, okay?

192
00:09:28,408 --> 00:09:31,790
Because three weeks of 60 hours, scientifically,

193
00:09:31,810 --> 00:09:35,032
is less productive, creatively, industrially.

194
00:09:35,052 --> 00:09:36,573
It doesn't matter what work you're doing,

195
00:09:36,593 --> 00:09:37,134
you're doing it worse.

196
00:09:38,054 --> 00:09:41,196
and your brain doesn't realize it because it feels awesome

197
00:09:41,256 --> 00:09:43,057
because you're putting in everything

198
00:09:43,097 --> 00:09:45,158
and you're bleeding all over it and it's great.

199
00:09:45,558 --> 00:09:46,538
But too bad.

200
00:09:47,799 --> 00:09:50,220
Those of you who have the magical thinking problem

201
00:09:50,300 --> 00:09:53,402
of thinking that you are special and exceptional to this,

202
00:09:53,582 --> 00:09:54,342
you are wrong.

203
00:09:55,023 --> 00:09:56,844
They actually did a study on people who think

204
00:09:56,864 --> 00:09:58,725
they need less than seven hours of sleep.

205
00:09:59,285 --> 00:09:59,945
They don't exist.

206
00:10:00,325 --> 00:10:03,407
Five out of 100 people who think that are correct.

207
00:10:03,667 --> 00:10:04,227
So 95 wrong.

208
00:10:04,267 --> 00:10:04,387
Yeah.

209
00:10:07,737 --> 00:10:12,178
The good news is that these secrets are actually just standard production.

210
00:10:13,019 --> 00:10:17,920
And production is a skill like any other skill and it's a really boring one that nobody thinks

211
00:10:17,980 --> 00:10:22,842
is very exciting, I guess, because programming, designing and art is much more exciting for

212
00:10:22,882 --> 00:10:23,722
my time, at least.

213
00:10:24,283 --> 00:10:28,304
But as long as you keep trying to get better, then you will, because that's how skills work.

214
00:10:29,701 --> 00:10:31,382
And it's important that you don't give up

215
00:10:31,823 --> 00:10:34,365
because you're going to keep making games.

216
00:10:34,465 --> 00:10:36,827
Even if you realize I haven't taken as good care of myself

217
00:10:36,987 --> 00:10:38,968
as I deserve, that's all right.

218
00:10:39,068 --> 00:10:41,370
Forgive yourself, be kind to yourself.

219
00:10:42,331 --> 00:10:43,512
Because we are primates.

220
00:10:44,273 --> 00:10:47,435
Primates need food and shelter and belonging.

221
00:10:48,336 --> 00:10:51,578
Primates need to be taken care of in a way that games don't.

222
00:10:52,539 --> 00:10:55,541
Burnout isn't really about working a certain number of hours.

223
00:10:55,761 --> 00:10:57,583
Everyone has different work habits.

224
00:10:58,263 --> 00:11:03,927
A few long nights aren't going to kill you, but a few long months might, especially when

225
00:11:04,007 --> 00:11:07,550
combined with death or disease or other problems that are real.

226
00:11:08,611 --> 00:11:11,173
Burnout is the feeling of becoming slowly dulled

227
00:11:11,534 --> 00:11:14,056
as layer after layer of exhaustion accumulates,

228
00:11:14,436 --> 00:11:15,277
weighing down on you.

229
00:11:15,938 --> 00:11:17,560
Burnout is the void left behind

230
00:11:17,620 --> 00:11:19,662
where the rest of your career would have been.

231
00:11:20,463 --> 00:11:22,545
Burnout is the exhausted bitterness

232
00:11:23,105 --> 00:11:25,468
where your passion and your excitement used to be.

233
00:11:26,909 --> 00:11:27,970
But you could choose differently.

234
00:11:28,791 --> 00:11:31,934
You don't have to suffer to make great games.

235
00:11:33,128 --> 00:11:35,751
The moment we are in right now will not come again.

236
00:11:36,472 --> 00:11:40,576
We are here in Moscone Center of San Francisco, USA,

237
00:11:40,877 --> 00:11:42,418
planet Earth, breathing this air

238
00:11:42,519 --> 00:11:45,662
and contemplating these great games because we're alive.

239
00:11:45,682 --> 00:11:49,166
And everyone here watching this at home

240
00:11:49,507 --> 00:11:50,848
or in this room will die.

241
00:11:53,107 --> 00:12:02,714
So, even if we create a masterpiece beloved for a thousand years, our existence here and now will be gone forever.

242
00:12:03,895 --> 00:12:14,823
So it's up to you to protect what time and love and joy you have left in you and not use it up making yourself feel more productive.

243
00:12:16,567 --> 00:12:20,211
If it helps, envision your dedication to self-care

244
00:12:20,331 --> 00:12:21,072
as a sword.

245
00:12:21,913 --> 00:12:24,695
See the darkness of burnout gathering around you

246
00:12:24,755 --> 00:12:27,358
as a shadow, stealing away your concentration

247
00:12:27,738 --> 00:12:29,080
and your still-beating heart.

248
00:12:29,840 --> 00:12:32,583
Be disciplined, warrior of light and courage.

249
00:12:33,164 --> 00:12:35,326
