Because of the coverage it got, it actually got a second bump, almost as big.

489
00:28:43,117 --> 00:28:45,158
as the initial sort of press it got.

490
00:28:45,738 --> 00:28:47,099
And so people were talking about the game.

491
00:28:47,139 --> 00:28:49,980
And at that point, this high-quality trailer,

492
00:28:50,040 --> 00:28:53,402
which was a parody of Kanye West's Power,

493
00:28:53,542 --> 00:28:57,504
except Shower was the theme, was released.

494
00:28:59,104 --> 00:29:03,829
The video was done by a guy called Everdrede who's currently working on the Tingler as well with Zoe Quinn

495
00:29:04,670 --> 00:29:09,695
And also did the trailer for Undertale, but this incredible high quality trailer came out a few days later

496
00:29:09,715 --> 00:29:12,899
And you can see that well it didn't get as many views

497
00:29:13,880 --> 00:29:18,504
Because of this high quality trailer it actually got more yes votes compared to the number of views

498
00:29:18,585 --> 00:29:20,166
It was a higher quality of view

499
00:29:20,727 --> 00:29:25,668
to the Steam Greenlight page than the initial low-quality trailer.

500
00:29:25,708 --> 00:29:29,809
So I was able to maximize the audience of who saw or who heard about the game.

501
00:29:30,589 --> 00:29:33,129
So by building up this facade and then subverting it,

502
00:29:33,730 --> 00:29:36,550
I was able to make the marketing of the game a little bit more memorable.

503
00:29:36,870 --> 00:29:39,311
And this is something that happens throughout the core game itself.

504
00:29:39,891 --> 00:29:44,092
So if you're not familiar with the game, it's a fast-paced dad-matching game.

505
00:29:44,732 --> 00:29:46,613
We have to guide your child to its dad.

506
00:29:47,393 --> 00:29:50,273
And there's a power-up there. You can see it's shaved the dad's.

507
00:29:51,614 --> 00:29:52,994
That's the entirety of the power-up.

508
00:29:54,375 --> 00:29:55,515
But that's the core gameplay loop.

509
00:29:55,535 --> 00:29:59,057
This is something that just happens as the game goes on.

510
00:29:59,417 --> 00:30:01,278
But then eventually, the next thing you know,

511
00:30:01,358 --> 00:30:02,918
you're in a point-and-click adventure game

512
00:30:02,998 --> 00:30:05,439
where you are a pantsless cop dad.

513
00:30:06,740 --> 00:30:09,501
And the idea is that you need to get the shower up and running again

514
00:30:09,581 --> 00:30:11,641
because the hot water system isn't working.

515
00:30:12,742 --> 00:30:14,883
You know, very much inspired by Frog Fractions.

516
00:30:16,972 --> 00:30:20,975
And the reason why these sort of moments are memorable to people is because it turns out

517
00:30:21,475 --> 00:30:22,876
people really fucking love surprises.

518
00:30:24,197 --> 00:30:28,260
So this is the results of a scientific study, I forgot which university it was but there's

519
00:30:28,280 --> 00:30:30,542
a link down the bottom left there if you want to look up more about it.

520
00:30:30,982 --> 00:30:34,625
What they did was they got these test subjects, these people, hooked them up to MRI machines

521
00:30:34,745 --> 00:30:37,967
and then at regular intervals squirted liquid into their mouth.

522
00:30:38,187 --> 00:30:40,349
It was either juice or water.

523
00:30:41,070 --> 00:30:43,032
And everyone had a preference for either juice or water.

524
00:30:44,433 --> 00:30:49,498
But what they found was that if you squirted liquid at an unpredictable rate, that actually

525
00:30:49,538 --> 00:30:53,863
drove enjoyment way more than if you got a preference for juice or water at a predictable

526
00:30:53,923 --> 00:30:54,143
rate.

527
00:30:54,904 --> 00:30:57,286
So people just loved the surprise aspect of it a lot more.

528
00:30:58,607 --> 00:31:01,227
But the subversion is just one aspect of the game.

529
00:31:01,648 --> 00:31:04,388
Obviously the incredibly long, ridiculous title

530
00:31:04,468 --> 00:31:04,988
acts as a hook.

531
00:31:05,969 --> 00:31:07,569
It's got a very accessible price point

532
00:31:07,589 --> 00:31:08,589
which encourages gifting.

533
00:31:09,610 --> 00:31:11,550
And the core gameplay loop, I reckon, anyway,

534
00:31:11,650 --> 00:31:13,191
is interesting enough on its own.

535
00:31:14,051 --> 00:31:16,771
But hopefully that inspires you to add

536
00:31:16,791 --> 00:31:18,912
a little bit more surprise and subversions in your game.

537
00:31:19,172 --> 00:31:19,392
Thank you.

538
00:31:34,723 --> 00:31:35,583
Thank you Marvin.

539
00:31:36,064 --> 00:31:36,484
All right.

540
00:31:49,092 --> 00:31:49,833
Please welcome Gemma.

541
00:31:58,300 --> 00:32:00,982
Hi, my name's Gemma, and I'm an indie developer.

542
00:32:01,582 --> 00:32:03,343
And ordinarily, in a venue like this one,

543
00:32:03,383 --> 00:32:05,584
that might sound like a weird sort of confession

544
00:32:05,704 --> 00:32:07,025
or even an attempt at humor,

545
00:32:07,645 --> 00:32:10,046
drawing upon the shared background level discomfort

546
00:32:10,106 --> 00:32:12,367
many of us might feel about this career path

547
00:32:12,407 --> 00:32:13,328
and medium we've chosen.

548
00:32:13,648 --> 00:32:15,229
Some sort of gallows humor, I guess.

549
00:32:15,849 --> 00:32:17,430
But for me, this is a genuine statement,

550
00:32:17,510 --> 00:32:19,651
which I actually find myself having to reinforce

551
00:32:19,831 --> 00:32:22,813
time after time to others as much as to myself.

552
00:32:23,473 --> 00:32:24,073
For example,

553
00:32:25,408 --> 00:32:27,910
A little while ago I was at a gathering of Stockholm indies,

554
00:32:28,131 --> 00:32:29,812
one I've attended for a couple of years now

555
00:32:29,892 --> 00:32:31,274
since that's the city where I live.

556
00:32:31,854 --> 00:32:34,177
Chatting away in a 400 year old beer cellar

557
00:32:34,237 --> 00:32:35,558
about this medium we all love,

558
00:32:35,979 --> 00:32:38,381
when the developer I'm talking to starts in surprise.

559
00:32:39,342 --> 00:32:40,944
You're an indie developer, he says?

560
00:32:40,964 --> 00:32:43,206
I thought you were just a student or something.

561
00:32:44,067 --> 00:32:46,449
It's an assessment which is not negative per se,

562
00:32:47,010 --> 00:32:48,651
but is also not at all rare for me.

563
00:32:50,045 --> 00:32:53,527
In correcting him, I had to explain how I've been in industry for six years,

564
00:32:53,687 --> 00:32:55,927
how instead I lecture students at universities,

565
00:32:56,207 --> 00:33:00,229
and how at the time I was working to found what is now a studio called Kaleidoscope.

566
00:33:00,929 --> 00:33:03,870
Despite having worked on around a dozen indie-scale projects,

567
00:33:03,930 --> 00:33:06,071
people still get surprised when I tell them that,

568
00:33:06,391 --> 00:33:09,112
apparently despite appearances, I am an indie.

569
00:33:09,572 --> 00:33:11,933
And I suspect I'm not the only one for whom this is the case.

570
00:33:13,147 --> 00:33:15,650
It's a problem which at first felt like one of gender bias,

571
00:33:15,690 --> 00:33:18,413
given that I do identify and present myself as female.

572
00:33:19,174 --> 00:33:21,316
Then I began to wonder about somehow broadcasting

573
00:33:21,356 --> 00:33:23,698
my own imposter syndrome, telepathically

574
00:33:23,759 --> 00:33:26,722
infecting the outside world with taints upon my own confidence.

575
00:33:27,721 --> 00:33:30,503
But when I worked to get over that particular kind

576
00:33:30,543 --> 00:33:32,684
of nonsense, I began to wonder if it's perhaps

577
00:33:32,724 --> 00:33:33,765
because of something else.

578
00:33:34,685 --> 00:33:37,046
What if the reason some of us don't pass for Indie

579
00:33:37,467 --> 00:33:39,148
is because our community and culture

580
00:33:39,168 --> 00:33:40,468
is still being misrepresented?

581
00:33:41,109 --> 00:33:43,070
Whilst we can all sit here and know that,

582
00:33:43,650 --> 00:33:46,252
from practical experience, and at least to some degree,

583
00:33:46,672 --> 00:33:48,433
the Indie sphere is a diverse one,

584
00:33:49,234 --> 00:33:51,835
the outside world, and therefore the stereotypical view

585
00:33:51,975 --> 00:33:54,357
of an Indie developer, arguably still see

586
00:33:54,397 --> 00:33:55,898
what we do as something like this.

587
00:33:56,989 --> 00:33:59,730
namely white men either crunching away in bedrooms

588
00:33:59,770 --> 00:34:01,571
and small offices surrounded by toys,

589
00:34:02,132 --> 00:34:04,233
or cafes and trendy co-working spaces

590
00:34:04,333 --> 00:34:05,894
surrounded instead by modern art.

591
00:34:06,575 --> 00:34:08,876
That said, part of our development process

592
00:34:08,936 --> 00:34:10,677
does take place in a London cafe,

593
00:34:10,797 --> 00:34:12,158
so for Kaleidoscope at least,

594
00:34:12,378 --> 00:34:13,839
there is a small element of truth

595
00:34:13,899 --> 00:34:15,260
in Jonathan Blow's muffin there.

596
00:34:17,047 --> 00:34:20,349
My point being that whilst these are not bad things in and of themselves,

597
00:34:20,669 --> 00:34:23,811
there are a slew of cultural trappings wrapped up in particularly the formal

598
00:34:23,891 --> 00:34:28,294
interpretation of what indie is, which at best misrepresent most of us and how we

599
00:34:28,355 --> 00:34:31,897
work, and at worst glamorize some rather horrifying working practices.

600
00:34:33,418 --> 00:34:36,100
Though amusing at first, images, articles, and ideas

601
00:34:36,140 --> 00:34:38,480
like that of the ramen scoffing bedsit dweller

602
00:34:38,761 --> 00:34:41,402
still saturate search terms relating to our own career

603
00:34:41,482 --> 00:34:41,762
niche.

604
00:34:42,382 --> 00:34:44,543
Nothing about this should really be aspirational.

605
00:34:44,703 --> 00:34:47,224
And yet for some, this notion of caffeine addicted,

606
00:34:47,324 --> 00:34:50,265
stay-at-home indies who have to be reminded to put clothes on

607
00:34:50,305 --> 00:34:52,866
and go outside in an embarrassing number of articles

608
00:34:53,546 --> 00:34:56,908
is somehow the lodestar which we and they are navigating towards.

609
00:34:57,888 --> 00:35:03,413
Insofar as we have any label, I'd rather espouse and aspire to the positive aspects of it, thank you very much.

610
00:35:04,314 --> 00:35:08,798
But why are these ideas of India's label and how Indy we are even important?

611
00:35:09,319 --> 00:35:11,681
I offer two main reasons, one of which is personal.

612
00:35:13,061 --> 00:35:15,182
Indie game development and the communities within it

613
00:35:15,242 --> 00:35:16,563
are a part of my identity.

614
00:35:16,904 --> 00:35:18,685
And when somebody I'm meeting for the first time

615
00:35:18,785 --> 00:35:21,547
cuts through pointless small talk to ask a good question,

616
00:35:21,727 --> 00:35:24,108
like, what do you choose to do with your limited time

617
00:35:24,188 --> 00:35:26,510
upon this earth, I like being able to say

618
00:35:26,550 --> 00:35:29,092
that I enjoy interactive and accessible experiences

619
00:35:29,132 --> 00:35:32,474
for people to enjoy, to learn from, escape to,

620
00:35:32,894 --> 00:35:35,776
or whatever it is that they and I fancy doing at that time.

621
00:35:36,897 --> 00:35:40,580
Another reason is broader reaching than that, and to bluntly summarize,

622
00:35:41,021 --> 00:35:46,126
I don't think that something as inspiring as what we should do should be seen, again stereotypically,

623
00:35:46,446 --> 00:35:51,671
solely as the domain of privileged individuals who can afford, financially or physically,

624
00:35:52,071 --> 00:35:53,813
to spend months on voluntary crunch.

625
00:35:54,634 --> 00:35:59,857
Working out of a backpack and generally letting standards of living slip for oneself and for

626
00:35:59,937 --> 00:36:04,761
one's collaborators just to get the game done doesn't work for everybody. Nor do I think

627
00:36:04,821 --> 00:36:09,204
anybody should feel pressured into that kind of lifestyle or be judged for having priorities

628
00:36:09,304 --> 00:36:12,226
elsewhere and therefore not being able to match up to that ideal.

629
00:36:13,650 --> 00:36:16,191
Do we really want indie to be seen as a single,

630
00:36:16,251 --> 00:36:18,012
homogenous strand of game creation?

631
00:36:18,392 --> 00:36:20,433
Or can we perhaps shift the focus ourselves?

632
00:36:20,913 --> 00:36:22,834
A five-minute soapbox is a tough space

633
00:36:22,874 --> 00:36:24,415
in which to try and offer solutions.

634
00:36:24,795 --> 00:36:27,797
But insofar as people do listen to us as indie creators,

635
00:36:28,177 --> 00:36:30,018
I think it's our duty to talk more about

636
00:36:30,078 --> 00:36:33,079
just what it is that we do, privileges, hardships, and all.

637
00:36:33,639 --> 00:36:35,500
So as to dispel the illusion that we're still

638
00:36:35,720 --> 00:36:37,881
all living an indie game-the-movie lifestyle.

639
00:36:38,992 --> 00:36:41,013
I'm afforded some social privileges myself.

640
00:36:41,393 --> 00:36:43,754
My place is that of one who can occasionally travel

641
00:36:43,794 --> 00:36:45,975
to game jams and conferences, and can

642
00:36:45,995 --> 00:36:48,096
devote a portion of her life to passion projects

643
00:36:48,256 --> 00:36:49,397
and to advocacy work.

644
00:36:50,157 --> 00:36:52,218
But in other ways, I am an atypical indie,

645
00:36:52,498 --> 00:36:55,280
as I suspect the vast majority of us actually are.

646
00:36:56,761 --> 00:37:01,764
So for venues beyond this one, let's see if we can shift the conversation a little bit,

647
00:37:02,004 --> 00:37:06,006
move the idea of indiness away from something which is literally all-consuming

648
00:37:06,306 --> 00:37:09,328
to one which is more realistic and frankly more respectful.

649
00:37:09,788 --> 00:37:13,550
Because our chosen place is that of indies and this space is what we make of it.

650
00:37:14,331 --> 00:37:14,591
Thank you.

651
00:37:29,452 --> 00:37:30,253
Thank you so much, John.

652
00:37:30,273 --> 00:37:30,934
That was great.

653
00:37:31,394 --> 00:37:31,714
All right.

654
00:37:37,760 --> 00:37:37,880
Oh.

655
00:37:41,903 --> 00:37:42,183
Jerry.

656
00:37:42,284 --> 00:37:42,984
Jerry.

657
00:37:45,226 --> 00:37:45,727
Jerry.

658
00:37:46,087 --> 00:37:47,348
Wait for it, Jerry.

659
00:37:49,029 --> 00:37:50,851
It's going to happen, Jerry.

660
00:37:50,891 --> 00:37:51,331
Hang in there.

661
00:38:00,364 --> 00:38:01,435
All right, please welcome Jerry.

662
00:38:09,705 --> 00:38:11,046
I don't think that bit ever gets old.

663
00:38:12,647 --> 00:38:13,368
I'm Jerry Bellick.

664
00:38:13,868 --> 00:38:16,570
I'm a professor of game design at Miami University.

665
00:38:17,290 --> 00:38:19,812
I'm also working on my MFA in experience design.

666
00:38:20,433 --> 00:38:24,295
And at Miami, I'm part of the interactive media studies

667
00:38:24,355 --> 00:38:24,996
department.

668
00:38:25,476 --> 00:38:28,318
We're hoping this fall that we will officially have our game

669
00:38:28,478 --> 00:38:30,059
design degree in place.

670
00:38:31,180 --> 00:38:32,521
I'm also an independent game designer.

671
00:38:32,661 --> 00:38:34,122
Being a teacher does not eliminate

672
00:38:34,182 --> 00:38:35,543
that part of my identity.

673
00:38:36,323 --> 00:38:42,948
I primarily do work in the medium of alternative controllers, hardware, electronics, but what

674
00:38:42,968 --> 00:38:48,992
I want to talk about is why we need to Venn harder in the industries of games and academia

675
00:38:49,372 --> 00:38:52,594
because they are not crossing over nearly as much as I think that they ought.

676
00:38:53,475 --> 00:39:00,596
So I think one of the biggest problems is we are lacking enough synthesis of all of the incredibly unique

677
00:39:00,676 --> 00:39:06,438
experiences that all of you have. It's starting to happen, and universities are starting to get

678
00:39:06,478 --> 00:39:10,899
interested, and they're starting to figure this stuff out, but we are going to lose a lot of

679
00:39:10,939 --> 00:39:17,000
incredible stuff considering the huge percentage of people that have come into the game industry,

680
00:39:17,360 --> 00:39:23,302
whether independent or in studios, through incredibly unique paths and different kinds of

681
00:39:23,302 --> 00:39:24,162
of experiences.

682
00:39:25,143 --> 00:39:26,844
So schools are taking it more seriously,

683
00:39:26,864 --> 00:39:28,445
but we still got a really long way to go.

684
00:39:28,465 --> 00:39:31,466
There are opportunities, however, for all of you

685
00:39:31,827 --> 00:39:35,309
to be involved without giving up your professional careers

686
00:39:35,549 --> 00:39:36,590
and your industry work.

687
00:39:37,610 --> 00:39:40,012
Academia wants you to stay involved in the industry.

688
00:39:40,072 --> 00:39:42,473
It's important that you do because that is where

689
00:39:42,493 --> 00:39:44,995
you're going to continue getting the kinds of experiences

690
00:39:45,975 --> 00:39:48,897
and unique perspectives that are going to benefit

691
00:39:49,197 --> 00:39:51,499
the students and the game designers of tomorrow.

692
00:39:52,399 --> 00:39:53,520
And you might accidentally like it.

693
00:39:54,421 --> 00:39:55,923
It's not bad.

694
00:39:57,885 --> 00:39:59,447
Educators can keep this up on their own.

695
00:39:59,727 --> 00:40:01,809
A lot of them don't have the experience in the first place,

696
00:40:02,470 --> 00:40:05,493
and we need a constant cycling and influx

697
00:40:05,554 --> 00:40:07,155
if we're going to keep that fresh.

698
00:40:08,377 --> 00:40:10,299
The disparity right now can feel a little bit awkward.

699
00:40:12,126 --> 00:40:15,747
So at Miami, I teach game design, development, pipeline,

700
00:40:15,807 --> 00:40:18,248
production, but as I said, alternative controllers

701
00:40:18,308 --> 00:40:19,228
are kind of my jam.

702
00:40:19,828 --> 00:40:22,109
And I started a class this semester teaching

703
00:40:22,129 --> 00:40:23,989
alternative controllers as a form of design,

704
00:40:24,289 --> 00:40:27,450
and it is the most interesting work that I have seen so far

705
00:40:27,490 --> 00:40:29,050
of any of my game design students.

706
00:40:29,471 --> 00:40:30,951
There's some practical reasons for that,

707
00:40:31,351 --> 00:40:33,472
but I also think that it has something to do

708
00:40:33,552 --> 00:40:35,692
with alternative controllers being the lens

709
00:40:35,752 --> 00:40:37,213
in which I view game design.

710
00:40:37,633 --> 00:40:40,673
It is how I have explored game design intimately.

711
00:40:40,954 --> 00:40:44,795
where I am most passionate and I think students are really responsive to that.

712
00:40:45,436 --> 00:40:48,757
You don't know what it is you know until you teach it and I think often you get

713
00:40:48,797 --> 00:40:52,419
really surprised by what it is that you do know. There is so much fresh

714
00:40:52,499 --> 00:40:57,681
territory and all of you have dug in such interesting places and we need you

715
00:40:57,781 --> 00:41:01,283
to take your personal lens and let students look through that for

716
00:41:01,323 --> 00:41:05,825
themselves. There are so many insights that you may have that you think are

717
00:41:05,865 --> 00:41:10,127
trivial that would be profound in the hands of the right minds, brain hands.

718
00:41:12,721 --> 00:41:16,242
I am sick of this argument when it comes to game design degrees.

719
00:41:16,742 --> 00:41:18,782
It drives me absolutely insane.

720
00:41:19,003 --> 00:41:20,063
We're trying to get them jobs.

721
00:41:20,083 --> 00:41:21,103
We're trying to teach them unity.

722
00:41:21,183 --> 00:41:22,103
No, they've got to make games.

723
00:41:22,163 --> 00:41:23,544
It's bullshit.

724
00:41:25,504 --> 00:41:27,785
I don't believe game design is a technical vocation.

725
00:41:28,645 --> 00:41:29,125
It is art.

726
00:41:29,225 --> 00:41:29,865
It is design.

727
00:41:29,905 --> 00:41:30,525
It is craft.

728
00:41:30,746 --> 00:41:31,406
Tools are great.

729
00:41:31,646 --> 00:41:35,167
Their design work should motivate their exploration into the technical.

730
00:41:36,047 --> 00:41:36,867
So what is a game designer?

731
00:41:38,025 --> 00:41:41,367
I don't know, but we can't forget to teach the design part of game design.

732
00:41:42,468 --> 00:41:46,912
Design exists for people, to evoke, to provoke, to help, to heal, to create meaning.

733
00:41:47,352 --> 00:41:52,276
So how can we complain about derivative, boring, cookie-cutter work, copies of copies, if students

