00:44:54,216 --> 00:45:03,504
and get in touch with me if you need more ideas. Thank you, Jerry. All right.

799
00:45:12,811 --> 00:45:13,572
Please welcome Bree.

800
00:45:21,265 --> 00:45:27,387
Oh, God. Okay. Hi, my name is Bree Code and I wanted to share with you everything I've

801
00:45:27,407 --> 00:45:32,008
learned about public speaking because somehow I've managed to travel full time for the past

802
00:45:32,088 --> 00:45:38,090
year and a bit speaking at conferences but I have absolutely no talent for this. The first

803
00:45:38,130 --> 00:45:41,051
time my boss asked me to speak on camera, I forgot my own name.

804
00:45:42,525 --> 00:45:42,846
I did.

805
00:45:43,846 --> 00:45:47,447
15 minutes before the second talk I ever gave, a man asked me if the seat next to me was

806
00:45:47,487 --> 00:45:51,789
taken and I was so nervous I couldn't understand his question and I couldn't answer and I just

807
00:45:51,809 --> 00:45:53,190
stared at him until he walked away.

808
00:45:55,391 --> 00:45:58,712
But with each mistake like this I've changed the way I do things and I have like a really

809
00:45:59,292 --> 00:46:00,192
strict process.

810
00:46:01,793 --> 00:46:07,155
So a week before the first good talk I ever gave, I met with my friend Jason to get feedback

811
00:46:07,335 --> 00:46:09,196
and he patiently listened to me talk about it.

812
00:46:09,516 --> 00:46:13,044
how great my slides were and how great I was for finishing them a week early.

813
00:46:13,064 --> 00:46:18,839
And then when I was done, he told me that out of my 60 slides, only one was interesting.

814
00:46:19,418 --> 00:46:21,399
He told me that I had to rewrite the whole talk,

815
00:46:21,800 --> 00:46:23,081
and he was right, because that slide

816
00:46:23,101 --> 00:46:24,502
was the only slide that was honest.

817
00:46:25,162 --> 00:46:27,284
I learned from Jason most things I know

818
00:46:27,324 --> 00:46:28,285
about how to write a talk,

819
00:46:28,785 --> 00:46:30,346
but especially I learned to start by thinking

820
00:46:30,386 --> 00:46:32,348
about what I care about and to work from there.

821
00:46:33,128 --> 00:46:34,629
Every talk I've given that fell flat

822
00:46:34,669 --> 00:46:35,850
was one where I was trying to say

823
00:46:35,930 --> 00:46:38,112
what I thought people wanted or needed to hear,

824
00:46:38,633 --> 00:46:40,474
and now I just talk about what I care about

825
00:46:40,574 --> 00:46:41,375
and it gets much better.

826
00:46:42,580 --> 00:46:44,683
I also decide who my audience is.

827
00:46:44,743 --> 00:46:48,828
I discovered that my talks are less clear and less effective when I try to speak to

828
00:46:48,928 --> 00:46:49,328
everyone.

829
00:46:49,789 --> 00:46:54,094
So now I just speak to inspire underrepresented people and not to try to convince any dudes

830
00:46:54,114 --> 00:46:57,959
who are stuck in their bad ways that they're wrong, because like our sworn enemy said,

831
00:46:57,979 --> 00:46:59,241
there are a lot of bad dudes out there.

832
00:47:01,233 --> 00:47:02,934
Once I know why I care about a topic

833
00:47:03,374 --> 00:47:05,295
and who I want to talk to, I make an outline.

834
00:47:05,895 --> 00:47:08,856
The outline is simple, but I follow a very specific order.

835
00:47:09,937 --> 00:47:11,537
First, why do I care about this talk?

836
00:47:12,258 --> 00:47:13,398
What am I trying to accomplish?

837
00:47:13,438 --> 00:47:14,419
Why do I care about that?

838
00:47:15,659 --> 00:47:17,820
Second, what is this thing that I care about?

839
00:47:17,980 --> 00:47:18,780
What are the details?

840
00:47:18,820 --> 00:47:19,721
What is my argument?

841
00:47:21,001 --> 00:47:23,903
Third, what does this mean for you all and for myself?

842
00:47:24,343 --> 00:47:26,404
What are the practical applications of this information?

843
00:47:26,444 --> 00:47:27,224
What are the next steps?

844
00:47:29,269 --> 00:47:31,609
And I'm a typical programmer, I'm methodical,

845
00:47:31,689 --> 00:47:33,270
and I'm detail-oriented, and I'm boring.

846
00:47:33,810 --> 00:47:36,171
And what I write, the first draft, is really boring.

847
00:47:36,611 --> 00:47:38,972
But I found a management study of techniques

848
00:47:39,012 --> 00:47:41,472
that turn boring leaders into interesting leaders.

849
00:47:42,173 --> 00:47:45,634
If you Google, can charisma be taught, you can find it.

850
00:47:46,234 --> 00:47:48,514
And I methodically go over each point in my outline,

851
00:47:48,594 --> 00:47:49,715
and I apply these techniques.

852
00:47:50,135 --> 00:47:52,996
I turn my ideas into stories, or lists, or questions,

853
00:47:53,116 --> 00:47:55,377
or metaphors, or contrasting points,

854
00:47:55,577 --> 00:47:57,197
and then people seem to like them better.

855
00:47:59,672 --> 00:48:01,794
And then once my outline is ready and it's more interesting,

856
00:48:01,914 --> 00:48:03,615
I just take each point of my outline

857
00:48:03,655 --> 00:48:04,595
and put them on a slide,

858
00:48:05,096 --> 00:48:06,076
and it generally works out

859
00:48:06,116 --> 00:48:07,738
to about one to two slides per minute.

860
00:48:09,178 --> 00:48:11,540
And then I go through and replace each idea with a picture.

861
00:48:11,560 --> 00:48:14,262
I get rid of as much text as possible,

862
00:48:14,322 --> 00:48:17,764
and I do that because I accidentally spent one talk

863
00:48:17,804 --> 00:48:19,505
just reading my slides to the audience

864
00:48:19,545 --> 00:48:21,066
and not saying what I'd planned to say.

865
00:48:21,086 --> 00:48:22,887
That was really terrible.

866
00:48:22,988 --> 00:48:24,649
And then in a talk this fall,

867
00:48:24,729 --> 00:48:27,090
halfway through I lost access to the notes on my screen.

868
00:48:27,372 --> 00:48:29,816
because there's always technical difficulties at conferences.

869
00:48:30,236 --> 00:48:32,079
And then I was horribly stuck without my notes.

870
00:48:32,500 --> 00:48:35,785
So now I know that the pictures not only need to be guides for the audience,

871
00:48:35,825 --> 00:48:37,087
but also for myself.

872
00:48:39,367 --> 00:48:40,468
And then when my slides are done,

873
00:48:40,508 --> 00:48:43,770
I practice a lot and get feedback.

874
00:48:44,010 --> 00:48:45,951
And I discover important things when I practice,

875
00:48:45,991 --> 00:48:48,313
not just with the writing, but with myself.

876
00:48:49,153 --> 00:48:50,774
The first time I wrote a one-hour talk,

877
00:48:50,834 --> 00:48:53,356
whenever I practiced, I kept panicking halfway through

878
00:48:53,796 --> 00:48:55,157
in my own apartment by myself.

879
00:48:56,037 --> 00:48:57,778
And I couldn't figure out why,

880
00:48:57,798 --> 00:48:59,219
because I'm very comfortable in my apartment.

881
00:48:59,940 --> 00:49:01,641
And by practicing enough times,

882
00:49:01,701 --> 00:49:02,922
I noticed that I was always panicking

883
00:49:03,002 --> 00:49:04,402
exactly at the 20-minute mark.

884
00:49:04,863 --> 00:49:07,124
And I realized that I was just never actually stopping

885
00:49:07,144 --> 00:49:07,905
to take a breath in.

886
00:49:10,767 --> 00:49:13,249
And I thought I was panicking, I was just out of breath.

887
00:49:14,509 --> 00:49:15,530
And then that made me panic.

888
00:49:16,990 --> 00:49:18,411
So now I remember to breathe.

889
00:49:19,332 --> 00:49:19,912
It's amazing.

890
00:49:19,932 --> 00:49:21,853
Which brings me to my final point.

891
00:49:23,673 --> 00:49:26,195
I will always be nervous before my talks.

892
00:49:26,795 --> 00:49:28,196
Emotions exist for a reason,

893
00:49:28,356 --> 00:49:30,338
and we get nerves before we talk

894
00:49:30,378 --> 00:49:32,159
because that energy helps us to deliver

895
00:49:32,539 --> 00:49:34,280
at least a slightly more energetic talk.

896
00:49:35,301 --> 00:49:36,882
So now when I feel nervous, instead of thinking,

897
00:49:36,902 --> 00:49:38,443
oh God, I'm so nervous, what if I faint

898
00:49:38,483 --> 00:49:39,924
in the middle of this, it's gonna be terrible,

899
00:49:40,365 --> 00:49:42,646
I think, oh God, I'm really nervous

900
00:49:42,686 --> 00:49:44,547
because I'm doing a talk and I need the energy,

901
00:49:44,948 --> 00:49:46,329
and then I'll feel better when it's done.

902
00:49:46,349 --> 00:49:49,071
And this helps me deal with that overwhelming anxiety

903
00:49:49,091 --> 00:49:51,312
that made me forget my own name on camera that first time.

904
00:49:52,245 --> 00:49:54,526
and I'm still really uncomfortable on stage.

905
00:49:54,606 --> 00:49:56,527
I forget to stand up straight, which I probably did,

906
00:49:56,567 --> 00:49:57,268
and I forgot again.

907
00:49:57,288 --> 00:50:00,909
And sometimes I forget to talk into the microphone.

908
00:50:01,089 --> 00:50:04,811
I've done that more times than it's really embarrassing.

909
00:50:06,192 --> 00:50:08,193
But I'm working on this, and I welcome your advice.

910
00:50:09,173 --> 00:50:11,114
And you can contact me on Twitter anytime

911
00:50:11,154 --> 00:50:12,575
if you have questions or advice,

912
00:50:12,715 --> 00:50:14,415
or if you need encouragement for your own talks.

913
00:50:14,916 --> 00:50:15,196
Thank you.

914
00:50:27,143 --> 00:50:27,985
Thank you, Bree.

915
00:50:37,603 --> 00:50:38,345
Please welcome Colm.

916
00:50:47,066 --> 00:50:49,228
Hi, everyone. My name is Colm Larkin,

917
00:50:50,089 --> 00:50:51,491
and I'm the founder of Gamberness,

918
00:50:51,851 --> 00:50:54,454
an indie studio from Dublin, Ireland.

919
00:50:55,895 --> 00:50:57,697
So I'm going to tell you a little story today

920
00:50:57,717 --> 00:50:59,720
about sharing your work, sharing your games,

921
00:51:00,621 --> 00:51:02,382
and why that's important and why that helped me.

922
00:51:04,705 --> 00:51:06,287
I made a game called Guilds of Dungeoneering.

923
00:51:06,867 --> 00:51:07,288
Came out in 2015.

924
00:51:10,532 --> 00:51:12,273
It was with a very, very small team.

925
00:51:12,893 --> 00:51:13,754
We had no budget.

926
00:51:14,374 --> 00:51:17,115
And against the odds, I guess, we were quite successful.

927
00:51:17,735 --> 00:51:20,957
And for me, my favorite parts of that success

928
00:51:21,137 --> 00:51:23,378
were appearing in print magazines

929
00:51:23,398 --> 00:51:25,279
and when we released on mobile,

930
00:51:25,299 --> 00:51:26,559
being on the front page of the App Store.

931
00:51:26,579 --> 00:51:27,440
That was amazing to me.

932
00:51:27,460 --> 00:51:31,961
And as I think back about why I was successful,

933
00:51:32,642 --> 00:51:34,843
I believe it was because I was sharing my work.

934
00:51:36,800 --> 00:51:38,721
When I started making Gilded Engineering,

935
00:51:39,521 --> 00:51:41,282
I decided to develop in the open.

936
00:51:41,922 --> 00:51:44,984
And I started a thread on TIG Source, which

937
00:51:45,064 --> 00:51:47,785
is a game development forum, and started just

938
00:51:47,825 --> 00:51:49,846
sharing playable versions of the game

939
00:51:49,886 --> 00:51:51,447
and asking for feedback from day one.

940
00:51:52,247 --> 00:51:53,288
And that was great.

941
00:51:53,408 --> 00:51:55,909
And I was basically following in the footsteps of people I admire

942
00:51:56,469 --> 00:51:59,871
and games I admire, like Fez and Minecraft and Papers, Please.

943
00:52:01,339 --> 00:52:05,762
And not only that, but I shared the idea for Guild of Dungeoneering

944
00:52:05,802 --> 00:52:09,605
before I ever started working on it to get feedback on that.

945
00:52:10,706 --> 00:52:14,669
And for me, sharing let me stop wasting my life

946
00:52:14,689 --> 00:52:17,431
not making games and actually finish some games,

947
00:52:18,412 --> 00:52:19,573
well before Guild of Dungeoneering.

948
00:52:20,113 --> 00:52:22,935
Let me become confident.

949
00:52:23,676 --> 00:52:25,517
And then when I did make a commercial game,

950
00:52:26,137 --> 00:52:27,619
I believe made it much more successful.

951
00:52:29,192 --> 00:52:35,295
So I just want to take a little time and talk to you about three things about sharing that I think are very important.

952
00:52:36,416 --> 00:52:40,217
So the first one is that your idea is not that special.

953
00:52:40,998 --> 00:52:47,900
So it's pretty common to have this romantic notion that you need an incredible idea to make a successful game,

954
00:52:48,701 --> 00:52:50,342
or that the idea is the only thing that matters.

955
00:52:50,822 --> 00:52:51,942
And I don't think that's true at all.

956
00:52:53,523 --> 00:52:55,025
I think execution is key.

957
00:52:55,705 --> 00:52:59,890
Iterating on your idea with feedback and sharing early,

958
00:52:59,910 --> 00:53:02,413
I think, helps you shape the vision of your idea

959
00:53:02,513 --> 00:53:03,594
into something interesting.

960
00:53:04,175 --> 00:53:07,339
I don't think an idea is actually all that important.

961
00:53:08,474 --> 00:53:13,198
And the second thing that I think is important about sharing

962
00:53:13,899 --> 00:53:16,501
is that no one is going to steal your idea.

963
00:53:17,162 --> 00:53:21,225
So this is a very common fear, I think even maybe an excuse

964
00:53:21,846 --> 00:53:24,688
we make to ourselves so we don't have to share things.

965
00:53:26,770 --> 00:53:28,611
you know, someone is going to see your idea

966
00:53:28,631 --> 00:53:30,272
and make a better game.

967
00:53:30,292 --> 00:53:31,572
And I don't think that's true.

968
00:53:31,792 --> 00:53:33,313
I mean, even if you share your idea

969
00:53:33,613 --> 00:53:36,195
and someone goes and makes a game based on that idea,

970
00:53:36,815 --> 00:53:38,576
your two games are going to be completely different

971
00:53:39,076 --> 00:53:39,937
by the time they come out.

972
00:53:40,317 --> 00:53:41,878
And if, you know, the worst happens

973
00:53:41,938 --> 00:53:45,099
and someone just wholesale copies your game and your idea

974
00:53:45,599 --> 00:53:47,240
and everything you've, you know, been sharing,

975
00:53:47,701 --> 00:53:48,821
well, I've got some good news for you

976
00:53:48,841 --> 00:53:51,222
because you basically have the moral high ground there

977
00:53:51,242 --> 00:53:52,463
and you have this public record of,

978
00:53:52,923 --> 00:53:53,844
you know, what you've been making.

979
00:53:54,644 --> 00:53:58,267
you get to go get some free PR and tell your story to the press, and that's cool.

980
00:54:00,009 --> 00:54:05,714
The final point I want to make is basically to share your work embarrassingly early.

981
00:54:06,454 --> 00:54:08,376
I think embarrassing is a very important word there.

982
00:54:09,177 --> 00:54:13,260
If you start sharing things you're proud of, you think are great,

983
00:54:14,492 --> 00:54:16,312
you've made a mistake, you're sharing too late.

984
00:54:17,372 --> 00:54:18,532
It's very important to start sharing

985
00:54:19,432 --> 00:54:21,153
when you're really embarrassed about what it is you're showing.

986
00:54:21,573 --> 00:54:22,833
And there's a few reasons for that.

987
00:54:23,433 --> 00:54:26,734
So if you start sharing really early,

988
00:54:27,314 --> 00:54:28,614
there's a few great things that happen.

989
00:54:28,654 --> 00:54:30,094
So you'll save yourself time,

990
00:54:30,134 --> 00:54:33,055
you won't end up going down some kind of rabbit holes of development

991
00:54:33,095 --> 00:54:34,035
thinking this will be good,

992
00:54:34,235 --> 00:54:35,715
because you're getting feedback immediately

993
00:54:35,795 --> 00:54:37,235
on whether that sounds interesting.

994
00:54:37,936 --> 00:54:42,116
And you'll get more basic feedback on basic parts of your game.

995
00:54:42,196 --> 00:54:43,297
So like the idea itself.

996
00:54:43,857 --> 00:54:46,759
the concept, the setting, the very bare mechanics,

997
00:54:47,519 --> 00:54:50,862
well before looking for feedback on more late stage stuff

998
00:54:50,902 --> 00:54:53,724
like polish and graphics quality.

999
00:54:54,525 --> 00:55:00,910
And this part is very hard, and practice makes perfect.

1000
00:55:02,856 --> 00:55:04,717
start doing this and it will get easier.

1001
00:55:04,898 --> 00:55:06,319
And the reason I think it's so hard

1002
00:55:06,739 --> 00:55:09,341
is that you are basically sharing your rough work,

1003
00:55:09,561 --> 00:55:11,162
your really bad work,

1004
00:55:11,603 --> 00:55:13,144
and you're kind of comparing it mentally

1005
00:55:13,204 --> 00:55:16,066
to the best finished work of people you admire.

1006
00:55:16,086 --> 00:55:18,188
And that is very difficult.

1007
00:55:19,068 --> 00:55:20,529
And I would suggest just trying it

1008
00:55:20,649 --> 00:55:23,171
and forcing yourself to do it because it gets easier.

1009
00:55:23,732 --> 00:55:25,994
And more than that, it really helps.

1010
00:55:26,514 --> 00:55:29,496
So I believe sharing and doing this has made...

1011
00:55:30,177 --> 00:55:35,760
me a better game developer has made the games I'm making better too. So I hope you try it.

1012
00:55:36,121 --> 00:55:36,421
Thank you.

1013
00:55:37,622 --> 00:55:45,467
APPLAUSE

1014
00:55:48,609 --> 00:55:50,250
Thank you Colm. All right.

1015
00:56:01,852 --> 00:56:03,493
Please welcome our final speaker, Jane.

1016
00:56:13,037 --> 00:56:13,778
Hello, everybody.

1017
00:56:14,198 --> 00:56:17,459
My name is Jane Ng, and I do 3D art at Campo Santo.

1018
00:56:17,639 --> 00:56:19,300
We shipped Firewatch last year.

1019
00:56:19,320 --> 00:56:23,762
I usually talk about environment art stuff, but today I'm going to talk about something

1020
00:56:23,882 --> 00:56:24,642
very different.

1021
00:56:25,443 --> 00:56:27,644
I'm going to talk about this.

1022
00:56:28,655 --> 00:56:35,117
This is a real candy bar. If it's not clear what's going on there, the tongue part is the candy.

1023
00:56:36,657 --> 00:56:42,619
So do you think it matters if that candy is any good at all? No, right? Because very few

1024
00:56:42,659 --> 00:56:49,282
people will want to try to eat that, right? This is a terrible product. And this is what I

1025
00:56:49,322 --> 00:56:54,883
really want to talk about today. Product and why it shouldn't be a dirty word for Indies.

1026
00:56:56,149 --> 00:56:58,891
Now, a while ago I saw this tweet and I forgot who it was from.

1027
00:56:59,051 --> 00:56:59,711
It doesn't matter.

1028
00:56:59,892 --> 00:57:04,515
I'm sure most of you have heard or seen something like this in your own circle.

1029
00:57:05,917 --> 00:57:11,201
There is, in my opinion, a general aversion to talking about our games as items of commerce.

1030
00:57:11,561 --> 00:57:13,783
But we really should just stop feeling weird about it.

1031
00:57:14,784 --> 00:57:19,368
In fact, if you sell your game in any way, shape or form on any platform and you need

1032
00:57:19,388 --> 00:57:24,232
to pay your bills, and I suspect a lot of us in this room do or want to, then we need

1033
00:57:24,252 --> 00:57:24,912
to talk about it.

1034
00:57:24,933 --> 00:57:25,113
Thank you.

1035
00:57:25,865 --> 00:57:30,108
Why? Because this is the age of Let's Play videos and refunds.

1036
00:57:30,768 --> 00:57:33,050
A lot of people, even people who love your game,

1037
00:57:33,510 --> 00:57:36,331
don't have to buy anymore to check it out or experience it.

1038
00:57:38,755 --> 00:57:42,938
Now as indies I've always been very grateful how supportive we are to each other.

1039
00:57:42,958 --> 00:57:47,781
And you know, you always can get help with your game idea or if you need feedback on

1040
00:57:47,801 --> 00:57:50,142
a prototype, you know, there's always help.

1041
00:57:50,743 --> 00:57:56,086
But I rarely see anyone ask, hey, what do you think of my copywriting?

1042
00:57:56,607 --> 00:58:00,509
Or even would you pay money for this if you saw this on Steam?

1043
00:58:02,163 --> 00:58:04,524
I know it's a very uncomfortable thing to ask

1044
00:58:04,825 --> 00:58:05,825
or even to think about,

1045
00:58:05,965 --> 00:58:08,526
because it is very uncomfortable to acknowledge

1046
00:58:08,566 --> 00:58:12,168
that a great game experience is not the same thing

1047
00:58:12,428 --> 00:58:14,048
as a good entertainment product

1048
00:58:14,088 --> 00:58:15,569
that people might want to buy.

1049
00:58:17,290 --> 00:58:18,190
Now in our ideals,

1050
00:58:18,250 --> 00:58:20,471
we think that great games should be rewarded,

1051
00:58:20,491 --> 00:58:23,092
that we think people should buy great games.

1052
00:58:23,952 --> 00:58:25,673
And we want it to be true so much

1053
00:58:25,853 --> 00:58:27,654
that we sometimes forget that this is not,

1054
00:58:27,714 --> 00:58:29,375
in fact, a causal relationship.

1055
00:58:31,712 --> 00:58:34,034
In game design, we are often urged to make decisions

1056
00:58:34,254 --> 00:58:36,476
in the interest of the player, and that's great.

1057
00:58:36,916 --> 00:58:39,458
And all I'm saying here is that we spend a little time

1058
00:58:39,859 --> 00:58:42,841
considering our game outside of the game experience itself

1059
00:58:43,262 --> 00:58:45,784
from the perspective of your potential player,

1060
00:58:46,545 --> 00:58:48,206
someone who has not even played your game.

1061
00:58:49,047 --> 00:58:51,449
Now, how would your game look to this potential player?

1062
00:58:52,049 --> 00:58:53,070
Is it attractive?

1063
00:58:55,056 --> 00:58:58,800
I strongly believe that you can have a game that people want to own that is also 100%

1064
00:58:59,801 --> 00:59:00,121
yours.

1065
00:59:00,701 --> 00:59:05,987
Evaluating your game honestly from the perspective of a consumer is not compromising the creative

1066
00:59:06,107 --> 00:59:07,708
integrity of your game at all.

1067
00:59:09,110 --> 00:59:10,971
And this is not just a business thing.

1068
00:59:11,292 --> 00:59:14,575
So don't fret about how, oh, but I don't have a business person.

1069
00:59:15,860 --> 00:59:17,621
In fact, I think a lot of this is really more

1070
00:59:17,641 --> 00:59:18,722
of a design problem.

1071
00:59:19,262 --> 00:59:22,025
And don't forget that product design is a big field

1072
00:59:22,065 --> 00:59:24,386
outside of games, and a lot of the lessons

1073
00:59:24,446 --> 00:59:25,908
do apply to video games.

1074
00:59:27,108 --> 00:59:29,610
The good news is, most game developers

1075
00:59:29,851 --> 00:59:31,532
are very well equipped to tackle

1076
00:59:31,612 --> 00:59:33,493
multidisciplinary design problems.

1077
00:59:34,074 --> 00:59:36,135
And a lot of aspects of making a good product

1078
00:59:36,676 --> 00:59:39,018
can involve your whole team, and it can be really fun.

1079
00:59:39,678 --> 00:59:42,280
And there's no one right way to make a good product.

1080
00:59:43,377 --> 00:59:49,018
The amazing thing about being indie is that you can do it however you want with your values.

1081
00:59:51,099 --> 00:59:54,060
Now some key points about some aspects of great products.

1082
00:59:54,920 --> 00:59:58,921
Actually this is way too big of a topic so I'm not going to talk about it and I'm also

1083
00:59:58,961 --> 00:59:59,601
not an expert.

1084
01:00:00,342 --> 01:00:05,683
And while we can probably agree on what is terrible, what is great is relative and it

1085
01:00:05,723 --> 01:00:06,663
depends on your audience.

1086
01:00:08,514 --> 01:00:10,436
And the key thing is to not neglect it.

1087
01:00:10,777 --> 01:00:12,418
Do spend some time thinking about

1088
01:00:12,478 --> 01:00:14,961
what makes a great entertainment product for you.

1089
01:00:16,363 --> 01:00:18,385
For me personally, every time I see a game

1090
01:00:18,465 --> 01:00:20,047
that I want to throw money at,

1091
01:00:20,107 --> 01:00:22,610
then I feel like that developer is doing something right.

1092
01:00:23,090 --> 01:00:25,753
And I do try to spend a little time thinking about

1093
01:00:26,154 --> 01:00:28,236
why I feel that way and try to learn from it.

1094
01:00:30,444 --> 01:00:32,606
So a good product is seductive.

1095
01:00:33,247 --> 01:00:34,849
A good product makes people want it

1096
01:00:35,109 --> 01:00:36,951
on their physical or digital shelf.

1097
01:00:37,531 --> 01:00:39,513
And you need to consider your whole package

1098
01:00:39,734 --> 01:00:42,436
and it needs to be attractive to people you think

1099
01:00:42,917 --> 01:00:45,179
would like the game inside the packaging.

1100
01:00:47,181 --> 01:00:49,604
So in short, just make sure your great game

1101
01:00:49,784 --> 01:00:51,666
isn't a Jar Jar Binks candy talk.

